subSection.paragraph:
With currently 54 described species, Ninetinae is the smallest subfamily in Pholcidae . The subfamily was originally established for a species from the Arabian Peninsula ( Simon 1890 ), and further species have been described from Africa (e.g., Huber 2000 ), but the large majority of currently known Ninetinae live in the New World. Here they are largely restricted and adapted to ‘unfavourable’ habitats with extreme temperatures, low humidity, and limited biodiversity. It is thus unsurprising that they hold several records for the family: the southernmost locality ( 47.687°S ; an unidentified species of
Gertschiola Brignoli
; M.A. Izquierdo pers. comm., 31 Jan. 2022 ), the northernmost locality ( 56.097°N ;
Pholcophora americana Banks
; Bennett 2014 ), and the highest locality ( 4450 m a.s.l.;
Nerudia centaura Huber
;
Huber et al. 2023a
). Most Ninetinae live in tiny spaces at ground level, under stones, in dead wood and cacti, or in the leaf litter. As a result, the spiders are small (body length usually 1–2 mm ) and short-legged, very unlike the ‘typical’ Pholcidae .

Sequence assembly and contamination check. The CO1 barcodes were assembled with Geneious Prime® 2023.1.2 (https://www.geneious.com), and taxonomic assignments were checked by: (1) blasting assembled sequences against a local NT database; (2) the identification engine of the Barcode of Life Data System (BOLD) (http://www.boldsystems.org/index.php) ( Ratnasingham and Hebert 2007 ;
Yang et al. 2020
).

Multiple sequence alignment (MSA) and tree construction. The CO1 barcodes were translated into protein sequences using BioPython (version 1.78) (

Cock 
et al.
2009

) with invertebrate mitochondrial genetic code. Next, protein-MSAs were constructed using the mafft-linsi algorithm of MAFFT (version 7.487) (
Katoh & Standley 2013
), which then assisted the construction of nucleotide level MSAs with PAL2NAL (

Suyama 
et al.
2006

). This helps avoid the introduction of biologically meaningless frameshifts to the alignments (

Suyama 
et al.
2006

). A neighbor-joining (NJ) tree (
Saitou & Nei 1987
) and genetic distances among specimens were calculated using the Kimura 2-parameter model (
Kimura 1980
) in MEGA 11 (

Tamura 
et al.
2021

), during which pairwise deletion of gaps in the alignment was applied. The NJ tree was assessed with 500 bootstrap replications (
Felsenstein 1985
). The online tool iTOL (
Letunic & Bork 2021
) was used for tree visualization.

